---
import { getCollection } from 'astro:content';
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { site } from '../lib/site';

const posts = await getCollection('posts', ({ data }) => !data.draft);
const since = '2019';
---

<Layout title="About" description={site.author.bio} current="/about/">
  <div class="wrap">
    <section class="about-hero">
      <img
        class="avatar"
        src={site.author.avatar}
        alt={`Portrait of ${site.author.name}`}
        width="128"
        height="128"
      />
      <div>
        <h1>{site.author.name}</h1>
        <p class="role">{site.author.role}</p>
        <p style="margin-top:1rem; color:var(--ink-soft); font-size:1.1rem;">
          {site.author.bio}
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <div class="prose" style="padding-top:2.5rem;">
      <p>
        <strong>Margins</strong> is where I keep what I figure out. I've spent the
        better part of a decade building interfaces — design systems, the
        unglamorous middle layer between a designer's file and a user's screen —
        and somewhere along the way I started writing the lessons down so I'd stop
        relearning them.
      </p>
      <p>
        The posts here split roughly in two. Half are <em>code</em>: small,
        durable patterns I reach for again and again — a state machine, a CSS
        layout, a built-in element most of us forgot existed. The other half are
        <em>essays</em>: arguments about why the web feels heavier than it should,
        and what we lost when we stopped trusting the platform.
      </p>

      <figure class="about-figure">
        <img
          src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1499750310107-5fef28a66643?auto=format&fit=crop&w=1200&q=80"
          alt="A writing desk in warm morning light with a coffee, a laptop, and an open notebook"
          loading="lazy"
          width="1200"
          height="800"
        />
        <figcaption>Where most of this gets written. Coffee is load-bearing.</figcaption>
      </figure>

      <h2>The short version</h2>
      <ul class="about-list">
        <li><b>Writing</b><span>Essays &amp; code, since {since} · {posts.length} posts and counting</span></li>
        <li><b>Day job</b><span>Frontend engineer focused on design systems and performance</span></li>
        <li><b>Tools</b><span>Plain Markdown, a static site builder, and a stubborn fondness for the cascade</span></li>
        <li><b>Based in</b><span>{site.author.location}</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Stay in touch</h2>
      <p>
        New posts land roughly twice a month. The most reliable way to follow
        along is the <a href="/rss.xml">RSS feed</a> — no algorithm, no inbox,
        just the writing when it's ready. Or find me on
        {site.social.map((s, i) => (
          <>
            {i > 0 ? (i === site.social.length - 1 ? ', and ' : ', ') : ''}
            <a href={s.href}>{s.label}</a>
          </>
        ))}.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
